1 Disk Partitioning
Check Disk Usage
df -h        # Disk usage in human-readable format
lsblk        # List block devices
fdisk -l     # List partition tables

Partition Disks (Standard Partition)
sudo fdisk /dev/sdb
# Follow prompts: n (new), p (primary), w (write)

2 Storage

Linux identifies disks as /dev/sda, /dev/sdb, etc.
Partitions: /dev/sda1, /dev/sdb1, etc.
Mounting partitions:
mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt
umount /mnt

3 Logical Volume Management (LVM)

LVM allows flexible disk management (resize volumes, combine disks).

Basic LVM Concepts
Physical Volume (PV) – Actual disk or partition.
Volume Group (VG) – Pool of storage from one or more PVs.
Logical Volume (LV) – Partition created from VG, mounted like a normal filesystem.

4 LVM Configuration During Installation

Select LVM option in installer.

Create VG from available PVs.

Allocate LV for /, /home, swap, etc.

5 Add Disk and Create Standard Partition
sudo fdisk /dev/sdc    # Create standard partition
mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdc1    # Format partition
mount /dev/sdc1 /mnt   # Mount

6 Add Disk and Create LVM Partition
# Create physical volume
sudo pvcreate /dev/sdd

# Create volume group
sudo vgcreate vg_data /dev/sdd

# Create logical volume
sudo lvcreate -n lv_data -L 10G vg_data

# Format and mount
mkfs.ext4 /dev/vg_data/lv_data
mount /dev/vg_data/lv_data /mnt/data

7 Extend Disk Using LVM
# Extend logical volume
lvextend -L +5G /dev/vg_data/lv_data

# Resize filesystem
resize2fs /dev/vg_data/lv_data

8 Adding Swap Space

Create swap file:

fallocate -l 2G /swapfile
chmod 600 /swapfile
mkswap /swapfile
swapon /swapfile

echo "/swapfile swap swap defaults 0 0" | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
